      <div xml:id="NA158-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">iḵtu āṟupārttu uṟṟa accattāl ciṟaippuṟamākac (ET: tōḻi) colliyatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is what was said while [HE] was behind the fence out of fear after having seen the path.</p>
      </div>
      <div xml:id="NA158">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            amma vāḻi tōḻi namvayiṉ</l>
<l>            yāṉō kāṇē ṉatutāṉ karantē</l>
<l rend="indent4">            vantaṉṟu maṉṉō kaṇṇē kaṇṇiṟ</l>
<l>            kallatar maṉṉuṅ kāṉkol lummē</l>
<l>            kaṉaiyiruḷ maṉṉuṅ kaṇkol lummē</l>
<l>            viṭarmukaic ceṟinta veñciṉa virumpuli </l>
<l>            pukarmuka vēḻam pulampat tākkik</l>
<l>            kuruti parukiya koḻuṅkavuṭ kayavāy</l>
<l>            vēṅkai mutaloṭu tuṭaikku</l>
<l>            mōṅkumalai nāṭaṉ varūu māṟē.</l>
            </lg>
       <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>Alas, oh friend, among us(?)<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">namvayiṉ</term>, 1st pl., is hard to integrate into the sentence, since the predicate is 1st sg., and as the exclusive nuance is already expressed by <term xml:lang="ta">yāṉō</term>, it is not quite clear what it contributes to the sense.</note></l>
<l>I, on my part, don't see it, having hidden itself.</l>
<l>{It has certainly come to the eye? For the eye,}</l>
<l>the forest, where the stony road stays, is killing.</l>
<l>The area, where intense darkness stays, is killing. (?!)<note place="foot">There seems to be a rather strong rhetoric flow in lines 1-4, but either with or without the additional line 2' the impact is completely unclear.</note></l>
<l>– the path along which the man from a land of high mountains is coming,</l>
<l rend="indent">where the hot-angered big tiger, that keeps to clefted caves,</l>
<l rend="indent">has attacked, for [its female?]<note place="foot">The topos usually is that the female elephant stays behind when the bull is killed, but here it is not worded. On the other hand, if we take, as would be more natural, the <term xml:lang="ta">vēḻam</term> as the subject of <term xml:lang="ta">pulampa</term>, we have no direct object for the <term xml:lang="ta">tākki</term>. Compare nevertheless version b.</note> to be lonely, the spotted-faced elephant bull</l>
<l rend="indent2">[and] wipes [its] deep mouth [and] fleshy(?)<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">koḻuṅ kavuḷ</term>: "fleshy cheek" - thus the explanation given by T.V.G.(?)</note> cheek,</l>
<l rend="indent2">that have drunken blood, with the base of the kino tree.</l>
<lg type="alternate" sameAs="5-8b">
    <l>where the spotted-faced elephant bull has on his own<note place="foot">It seems just about possible to take the <term xml:lang="ta">pulampa</term> here in an adverbial way.</note> attacked</l>
 	<l>the hot-angered big tiger, that keeps to clefted caves,</l>
     <l>[and now] wipes [its] deep mouth [and] rich temple<note place="foot">Since both <term xml:lang="ta">kavuḷ</term> and <term xml:lang="ta">kayavāy</term> are usually epithets of the elephant (just as ruining trees is bull elephant occupation) one might think about taking <term xml:lang="ta">vēḻam</term> as the subject, but then, as T.V.G. rightly points out, one would have to surmise that the elephant is carnivorous (which it usually is not, even in <term xml:lang="ta">Caṅkam</term> poetry). On the other hand, it seems possible to take <term xml:lang="ta">parukiya</term> in a less literal sense: face and mouth of the elephant are simply stained with blood after the attack. But there again it has to be pointed out that the blood is usually said to be found on the tusks.</note>, that have</l>
     <l>drunken blood, with the base of the kino tree.<note place="foot">Or: "[and] destroys the Vēṅkai tree along with [its] base".</note></l>
</lg>
        </lg>
